  "prompt": "Is the elephant-headed god \"Ganesh\" or \"Ganesha\"?",
  "response": "Both \"Ganesh\" and \"Ganesha\" refer to the same deity in Hinduism, the elephant-headed god known as the remover of obstacles and the god of beginnings, wisdom, and intellect. The difference in spelling is primarily due to transliteration from the original Sanskrit name **\u0917\u0923\u0947\u0936**, which can be written as \"Ganesha\" or \"Ganesh\" in English.\n\n- **Ganesha** (\u0917\u0923\u0947\u0936\u093e) is a more formal and complete transliteration, often preferred in scholarly or traditional contexts.\n- **Ganesh** (\u0917\u0923\u0947\u0936) is a more commonly used, simplified form in everyday language and modern contexts.\n\nBoth are correct and widely accepted, so the choice between them often depends on personal or regional preference.",
